resultVideos.Title: Jorma Sipilä: Onko julkisten palveluiden yksityistäminen uhka universalismille?
resultVideos.Description:
"Julkisten palveluiden yksityistäminen ei ole vaarallista, jos se pysyy valtion hanskassa", emeritusprofessori Jorma Sipilä sanoo.

Taustalla olevan valtion tulee olla demokraattinen ja hallita kokonaisuutta.

"Tällä hetkellä elinkeinoelämä kuitenkin uhkaa ottaa pyöritettäväkseen valtiolle kuuluvat toiminnat, ja valtion ote irtoaa", Sipilä pohtii.

Sipilän mukaan suunta on kohti mallia, jossa palveluita tuotetaan vain niille, kenellä on rahaa.

"Tällöin universalismi kyllä katoaa."

Valtion aseman vahvuus määrittää pitkälti, miten julkisten palveluiden yksityistäminen vaikuttaa universalismiin.

_____________________________________________

recommandationVideos.Title: Tohmajärveltä taistellen Syvärille 1941
recommandationVideos.Description:
Jalkaväkirykmentti 9. perustettiin kesäkuussa 1941 Kontiolahdessa 9. prikaatin varusmiehistä ja Pohjois-Karjalan suojeluskuntapiirin reservijoukoista. Rykmentti liitettiin eversti Antero Svenssonin 7. divisioonaan yhdessä jalkaväkirykmenttien 30 ja 51 kanssa. 
Karjalan Armeijan joukko-osastot etenivät valtakunnanrajan yli vanhaan Suomen karjalaan 10. heinäkuuta kello 17.00 alkaen. Eteneminen vanhan Suomen Karjalan alueella jatkui rankkojen taistelujen saattelemana aina Sortavalaan saakka, jonne saavuttiin 15. elokuuta 1941.
Etenemistä jatkettiin 23. elokuuta Koivuselkään ja siletä edelleen Uomaan kylään. Elokuun lopussa 1941 rykmentti ylitti vanhan rajan Käsnäselän ja Kolatselän välissä. Jalkaväkirykmentti yhdeksän taisteli syyskuussa Aunukseen kuuluvissa Nirkan, Pyhäjärven, Kaskanan ja Latvan erämaissa lokakuun alkuun saakka. 
Syvärin joki ylitettiin 6. lokakuuta 1941 kolmannella yrityskerralla. Marraskuussa 1941 eteneminen päättyi Ostan, Goran ja Horomovitsin linjalle. Näissä asemissa Jalkaväkirykmentti yhdeksän oli kesään 1944 saakka.
Tällä videolla kerron kesän ja syksyn 1941 JR 9:n taisteluista Tohmajärveltä aina Syvärin taakse Levinaan ja Baranyn takaisiin kyliin saakka.  Lähteenä tällä videolla olen käyttänyt sotapäiväkirjoja ja kolmea 2010-luvulla tekemiäni sotakirjoja. Kirjojen tekemisen taustalla oli isäni ja hänen neljä veljeä, jotka palvelivat koko sodan ajan Jalkaväkirykementti yhdeksän eri pataljoonissa.
Isäni toimi jatkosodan aikana II/JR 9 konekiväärimiehenä. Hänen esimiehenä oli lähes koko sodan ajan Mannerheim-ristin ritari Ahti Vuorensola.

recommandationVideos.Title: Jyväskylän tuhoisa junaturma (1998)
recommandationVideos.Description:
Jyväskylän ratapihalla tapahtui perjantai iltapäivänä 6.3.1998 vakava junaonnettomuus, jossa Turusta Pieksämäellä matkalla ollut matkustajajuna P105 suistui kiskoilta. 

Onnettomuudessa kuoli toinen veturinkuljettajista ja yhdeksän matkustajaa. Tämän lisäksi lähes 100 ihmistä loukkaantui. Kaiken kaikkiaan junassa matkusti noin kolmisensataa matkustajaa.

Kun matkustajat pääsivät ulos pystyssä pysyneistä vaunuista heitä kohtasi lohduton näky. Kaatuneiden vaunujen alta näkyi käsiä ja jalkoja, jotka edelleen liikkuivat. Onnettomuudessa mukana olleet ihmisiä ovat kuvailleet, että hetki onnettomuuden jälkeen vallitsi hyytävä hiljaisuus ja vain muutama valitus kuului. Epätoivoa lisäsi myös se, että tonneja painavien junavaunujen alta oli tavallisen ihmisen lähes mahdotonta pelastaa ihmisiä.

Onnettomuuden syitä katsottiin olevan 5 kappaletta, jotka tapahtumajärjestyksessä ovat seuraavat.

1. Väsynyt kuljettaja
2. Tähystäjä ei suorittanut tehtäväänsä
3. Kuljettajan väärä mielikuva oikeasta raiteesta
4. Opastimien samankaltaisuus
5. Viive jarruttamisen aloittamisessa

recommandationVideos.Title: Runebergin päivän viettoa kotimuseossa
recommandationVideos.Description:
Videotallenteessa pääsemme tutustumaan, miten kansallisrunoilijan syntymäpäivään liittyvät perinteet elävät nykyään kotimuseossa.  

Johan Ludvig Runebergin syntymäpäivään liittyi perinteitä jo hänen elinaikanaan. Esimerkiksi lukiossa opiskelevat pojat tulivat Runebergin ikkunan alle laulamaan. Fredrika otti kieloja syksyllä kellariin, ja joulun jälkeen hän herätteli niitä kukintoon, jotta runoilija sai nauttia lempikukkansa tuoksusta syntymäpäivänään. Muun muassa tämä perinne elää vielä, ja 5. helmikuuta kotimuseossa on aina kieloja esillä.

Tuotanto Porvoon kaupungin kulttuuripalvelut yhteistyössä Porvoon Museon kanssa.
recommandationVideos.Author: Porvoo - Borgå

recommandationVideos.Title: Tohmajärveltä taistellen Syvärille 1941
recommandationVideos.Description:
Jalkaväkirykmentti 9. perustettiin kesäkuussa 1941 Kontiolahdessa 9. prikaatin varusmiehistä ja Pohjois-Karjalan suojeluskuntapiirin reservijoukoista. Rykmentti liitettiin eversti Antero Svenssonin 7. divisioonaan yhdessä jalkaväkirykmenttien 30 ja 51 kanssa. 
Karjalan Armeijan joukko-osastot etenivät valtakunnanrajan yli vanhaan Suomen karjalaan 10. heinäkuuta kello 17.00 alkaen. Eteneminen vanhan Suomen Karjalan alueella jatkui rankkojen taistelujen saattelemana aina Sortavalaan saakka, jonne saavuttiin 15. elokuuta 1941.
Etenemistä jatkettiin 23. elokuuta Koivuselkään ja siletä edelleen Uomaan kylään. Elokuun lopussa 1941 rykmentti ylitti vanhan rajan Käsnäselän ja Kolatselän välissä. Jalkaväkirykmentti yhdeksän taisteli syyskuussa Aunukseen kuuluvissa Nirkan, Pyhäjärven, Kaskanan ja Latvan erämaissa lokakuun alkuun saakka. 
Syvärin joki ylitettiin 6. lokakuuta 1941 kolmannella yrityskerralla. Marraskuussa 1941 eteneminen päättyi Ostan, Goran ja Horomovitsin linjalle. Näissä asemissa Jalkaväkirykmentti yhdeksän oli kesään 1944 saakka.
Tällä videolla kerron kesän ja syksyn 1941 JR 9:n taisteluista Tohmajärveltä aina Syvärin taakse Levinaan ja Baranyn takaisiin kyliin saakka.  Lähteenä tällä videolla olen käyttänyt sotapäiväkirjoja ja kolmea 2010-luvulla tekemiäni sotakirjoja. Kirjojen tekemisen taustalla oli isäni ja hänen neljä veljeä, jotka palvelivat koko sodan ajan Jalkaväkirykementti yhdeksän eri pataljoonissa.
Isäni toimi jatkosodan aikana II/JR 9 konekiväärimiehenä. Hänen esimiehenä oli lähes koko sodan ajan Mannerheim-ristin ritari Ahti Vuorensola.

recommandationVideos.Title: Jyväskylän tuhoisa junaturma (1998)
recommandationVideos.Description:
Jyväskylän ratapihalla tapahtui perjantai iltapäivänä 6.3.1998 vakava junaonnettomuus, jossa Turusta Pieksämäellä matkalla ollut matkustajajuna P105 suistui kiskoilta. 

Onnettomuudessa kuoli toinen veturinkuljettajista ja yhdeksän matkustajaa. Tämän lisäksi lähes 100 ihmistä loukkaantui. Kaiken kaikkiaan junassa matkusti noin kolmisensataa matkustajaa.

Kun matkustajat pääsivät ulos pystyssä pysyneistä vaunuista heitä kohtasi lohduton näky. Kaatuneiden vaunujen alta näkyi käsiä ja jalkoja, jotka edelleen liikkuivat. Onnettomuudessa mukana olleet ihmisiä ovat kuvailleet, että hetki onnettomuuden jälkeen vallitsi hyytävä hiljaisuus ja vain muutama valitus kuului. Epätoivoa lisäsi myös se, että tonneja painavien junavaunujen alta oli tavallisen ihmisen lähes mahdotonta pelastaa ihmisiä.

Onnettomuuden syitä katsottiin olevan 5 kappaletta, jotka tapahtumajärjestyksessä ovat seuraavat.

1. Väsynyt kuljettaja
2. Tähystäjä ei suorittanut tehtäväänsä
3. Kuljettajan väärä mielikuva oikeasta raiteesta
4. Opastimien samankaltaisuus
5. Viive jarruttamisen aloittamisessa

recommandationVideos.Title: क्या Stock Market का Timing सच में बढ़ेगा | Brokers Body Response to SEBI
Keywords: Nse trading hours extended latest news
trading hours extended in india news
recommandationVideos.Description:
In the stock market, traders currently trade from 9:15 am to 3:30 pm, Monday to Friday. However, last year in September, the NSE (National Stock Exchange) sent a proposal to SEBI (Securities and Exchange Board of India) suggesting an extension of trading hours from 6 to 9 pm in the evening, and possibly even extending it till 11:30 pm in the future.

SEBI responded by stating that they would internally consult with various stakeholders such as brokers, associations, and depositories before making any decision. Now, a new development has occurred where brokers' associations have provided written confirmation to SEBI regarding this proposal.

In this video, we will explore the confirmation received and discuss what might happen next.
Many brokers, big and small, exist in the market. They form different associations. The main ones are the Bombay Stock Exchange and ANMI (Association of National Exchange Members of India). In September 2023, a new organisation called ISF (Industry Standard Forum) was formed over these two. ISF will communicate with them and eventually convey their discussions to SEBI (Securities and Exchange Board of India).

Apart from this, SEBI also releases a discussion paper in some cases, seeking views and thoughts from the general public regarding these situations.

Now, after listening to all these authorities, SEBI will release a discussion paper in which even ordinary traders will be asked whether the market should be kept open till late evening and whether it should be kept open until 11:30 onwards.

But as of today, ANMI has given its approval to ISF and has stated that for the proposed timing of 6 p.m. to 9 p.m., attention must be paid to the margin and trade files, which involve administrative tasks. But from our end, there is approval for extending trading timings.

However, the Bombay Stock Exchange has requested a little more time for consideration and has stated that they will inform by the end of February whether the stock market timings should be extended or not.

After hearing from the Bombay Stock Exchange and the Association of National Exchanges of Members of India, the matter will go to the Securities and Exchange Board of India (SEBI), and then a final decision will be made. 

Now, here's an interesting thing that full-service brokers who operate through relationship managers, offline branches, or franchises have a concern. They don't want the stock market timings to increase. 

But on the other hand, discount brokers are saying that increasing trading time will be beneficial because they won't incur any additional costs. When the discussion paper comes out, traders should also express their views, so that SEBI can make the right decision.

Now, in all this, let's discuss whether extending trading hours will be beneficial or harmful to you, and if there will be any advantages or disadvantages, what would they be?

recommandationVideos.Title: Zee Business Experts’ ₹7.41 Crore Fraud Caught by SEBI, Front Running | Fake Finfluencers Ep-7
Keywords: zee business expert caught by sebi
recommandationVideos.Description:
The Securities Exchange Board of India (SEBI) recently took action against Kiran Jadhav, Ashish Kelkar, Himanshu Gupta, Mudit Goyal, and Simi Bhaumik for breaking stock market rules. These individuals were accused of manipulating the market, cheating investors, and doing other illegal things. They were also accused of using their appearances on Zee Business TV to do these bad deeds.

These people were called 'experts' in the stock market. They had their own shows on Zee Business. Kiran Jadhav and Ashish Kelkar's show was called "Kiran Ka Kamal," Himanshu Gupta was "Hitman Himanshu," and Mudit Goyal's was "Mudit Ke Munafe." Simi Bhaumik had a show called "Simi Ke Non Stop Shares."

These "experts" worked with traders to make money illegally from the stock recommendations they gave on Zee Business. SEBI found out they made about ₹7.41 crore in less than a year by doing these bad things from February 1, 2022, to December 31, 2022. SEBI investigated them for over a year and found them guilty.

During their time on Zee Business, they worked with a trader named Nirmal Kumar Soni. He gave them a plan: they would tell him about the stock recommendations they were going to make on TV. Then, he would trade before everyone else and make money when the stock prices changed because of their recommendations. Soni promised to share the profits with them.

Soni used the early information about stock recommendations to trade for SAAR Commodities Private Limited, Manan Sharecom Private Limited, and Kanhya Trading Company. Some people associated with these companies were also involved in the crime.

Simi Bhaumik was especially greedy. She not only took the illegal profits from Soni but also got her husband, Pratha Sarathi Dhar, involved in trading using the same scheme.

All five offenders shared their recommendations before the TV show with Soni and Simi's husband. They used different phone numbers, SIM cards under fake names, and coded messages to hide their actions.

SEBI has told the offenders to give back the illegal profits and pay interest. They also can't trade stocks for a while, and the registered ones can't give advice.

There are some problems in the system that let these things happen. People don't need to be registered with SEBI to give stock advice on TV. Zee Business hired Mudit Goyal, who wasn't even registered. The rules for registered people and those who aren't aren't very different. With so many people giving advice on TV and social media, there needs to be better rules to stop this from happening again.

SEBI Regulation - https://www.sebi.gov.in/enforcement/orders/feb-2024/in-the-matter-of-trading-based-on-the-stock-recommendations-given-by-guest-experts-appearing-on-zee-business-channel_81278.html

recommandationVideos.Description:
What happened when Tucker Carlson met Vladimir Putin? Was it news, propaganda, theatre, or all three? Ian Bremmer breaks down what you need to know now in his latest Quick Take. 

Subscribe to GZERO on YouTube and turn on notifications (🔔): http://www.youtube.com/@GZEROMedia 
Sign up for GZERO Daily (free newsletter on global politics): https://rebrand.ly/gzeronewsletter

Ian Bremmer weighs in on Tucker Carlson's highly-anticipated interview with Putin and why it revealed what he and all other megalomaniacs have in common. The two-hour sit-down dropped to much fanfare from all sides of the political spectrum. Will there be any fallout from Putin’s first interview with an American since the start of the “special military operation” in Ukraine? Ian breaks down what you need to know in his latest Quick Take.

Hi, everybody. Ian Bremmer here. And a Quick Take, but towards the end of your week. Why? Because a lot of us watched this interview between Vladimir Putin and Tucker Carlson. And isn't there a lot to talk about? And the answer is a little less than all of the hype but still worth discussing.

First, I mean, you know, I will admit to having posted a fair bit about the importance of this interview. Of course, in part, it's because I have a history talking about, studying, covering Russia. But also, because this is now entering almost the third year of war when the Russians have invaded Ukraine, it is increasingly not going very well for the Ukrainians and therefore not very well for the United States and its allies. And that means that the timing of this interview is important, especially in the context of a very heated, very divisive US election, when increasingly support for Ukraine is becoming a matter of political difference. And it wasn't six months ago, but it certainly is becoming so very rapidly now.

Secondly, I have absolutely no problem with the idea of interviewing dictators. I think it's important for people to understand what makes everyone tick - friends, adversaries, everyone around the world. The problem is, of course, that dictators usually don't respect free press. And in Russia in particular, the media is, an independent media shut down, and they're imprisoned. They're sometimes assassinated. And certainly, Putin is not someone that has a history of valuing people that ask him independent minded, tough questions.

► CHAPTERS:
00:00 Intro: To   Gerund
00:32 When to use the To Infinitive
1:56 To   Gerund After Phrasal Verbs
4:02 Used to   Gerund
5:50 Confess and Admit to Gerund
6:36 More verbs followed by the Gerund 

 *   *   *

► TRANSCRIPTION
To go is wrong.

To going is right.

But wait a second.

I thought one of the most basic rules in English is that the infinitive of the verb is always to go, to eat, to take.

Well, in this video, I'm going to show you why this is wrong and why you should use 'to' plus the 'ing form,

to going

to taking

to eating instead. Are you ready?

Okay, first things first. I'm not saying that "to go" is always wrong. I'm just saying that it's not always right. In fact, in many, many, many common sentences, you will hear verbs in the infinitive with 'to', like I want to go on holiday.

I don't know whether to call her.

I'm too shy to sing in public.

The problem is that most of my students apply this rule for every situation. They say the word 'to' and they think, Oh, easy. It's the base form. So to go, to call, to sing.

And the problem is that this leads to a lot of common mistakes, mistakes I correct all the time and mistakes I don't want you to make. Now, the cool thing is that it's pretty easy to know when you need the '-ing' form of the verb.

And here's the secret. Once I've told you the secret and you've learned this grammar, you can complete this lesson by downloading some exam-style exercises that I've made for you, so you can actually use this grammar in context and remember it.

Okay, the link to those exercises is up there, and there's also a link in the description for you. Right.

The first thing you need to know is that using 'to' plus '-ing' is only possible when it comes after special verbs, a lot of which are phrasal verbs. Phrasal verbs that contain a verb, and the preposition 'to' at the end. And this 'to' is part of the verb.

A common example of this is 'look forward to'. The verb is to look forward to. And if you say, I look forward to meet to you next week, or I'm looking forward to hear from you, that's wrong.

And it's a really, really common mistake. You see, the word 'to' is part of the verb 'look forward to'. We always follow this verb with a noun or a gerund. Followed by a noun, it looks like this.

I look forward to the concert.

He's looking forward to the day he sees you again.

And followed by gerund, that's the ing form of the verb, it looks like this.

I look forward to meeting you next week.

He's looking forward to seeing you again.

Another example of this is the phrasal verb 'get round to', which we use to express the idea of finally doing something after a delay or procrastination. And again, because 'to' is part of the verb, we follow it with a gerund.

I finally got round to cleaning the car yesterday.

Did you get round to taking the book back to the library?

Now, it's not just phrasal verbs where this happens. There are many other verbs that always go with 'to'. So we're going to have a look at a few common verbs, and I'll divide them up into small categories to make it easier to remember for you. So first, let's have a look at some verbs related to change. They are 'be used to', 'get used to', and 'be accustomed to'.

recommandationVideos.Title: Perspective: AI in Education | 20 April, 2023
recommandationVideos.Description:
Technology has always played an important role in education but its current use is more prevalent than ever thanks to the increased availability of smart devices and web-based curriculum. A new dimension has been added with advances in the field of Artificial Intelligence. The National Education Policy of 2020 (NEP 2020) recognized the immense potential of AI and recommended its integration into the education system. To increase technology integration in schools, the CBSE in October last year introduced Artificial Intelligence (AI) and the Internet of Things (IoT) in the school curriculum from classes VI to X. AI has the potential to transform education by making it more efficient, effective, and accessible to students worldwide. However experts say it is crucial to ensure that the use of AI in education is ethical and responsible, and that it complements the work of human teachers rather than replacing them.

recommandationVideos.Title: Advocata Economic Freedom Summit 2024: From Crisis to Prosperity
recommandationVideos.Description:
The Advocata Economic Freedom Summit 2024 brings together leading thinkers and doers to deliberate on the state of economic freedom in Sri Lanka. In two separate events, in two different locations they discussed, debated and contemplated on ideas on how to improve levels of economic freedom in Sri Lanka and to provide audit of Sri Lanka's ratings on the acclaimed Economic Freedom of the World Index.

The Advocata Institute's Economic Freedom Summit 2024, commenced on January 29th at Marriott Courtyard, with a breakfast forum on 'Economic Freedom & its Pathway to Prosperity' 

The keynote speaker for this session was Thilan Wijesinghe (Chairman & CEO, TWCorp (Pvt) Ltd)
The speakers for the session included Fred McMahon (Resident Fellow, Fraser Institute), Dr. Tom G. Palmer (Executive Vice President, International Programs, Atlas Network), Dr.Harsha de Silva (Member of Parliament & Chairman, Committee on Public Finance), Daniel Alphonsus (Director, Advocata Institute) and Thilan Wijesinghe.

The session was moderated by Prof. Rohan Samarajiva (Board of Advisor, Advocata Institute)

The presentations by Thilan Wijesinghe and Fred McMahon can be accessed on our website https://www.advocata.org/media-archives/29/01/2024/advocata-economic-freedom-summit-24-economic-freedom-its-pathway-to-prosperityeconomicfreedomsummit2401-y7f68-kncds

recommandationVideos.Title: Strategies for becoming less distractible and improving focus | Nir Eyal
recommandationVideos.Description:
Nir Eyal is the author of two best-selling books, Hooked: How to Build Habit-Forming Products and Indistractable: How to Control Your Attention and Choose Your Life. He writes, consults, and teaches at the intersection of psychology, technology, and business. His books have sold over 1 million copies in more than 30 languages; he has taught at Stanford’s Graduate School of Business and its Design School; and he has started and sold two startups since 2003. In our conversation, we discuss:
• Strategies for becoming less distractible and improving focus
• The difference between distraction and “traction”• Reactive work vs. reflexive work and why you should book time in your calendar
• The 10-minute rule to overcome internal triggers and stay focused
• The problem with to-do lists, and what to do instead
• The value of creating a timebox schedule that aligns with personal values and priorities
• The use of pacts as a last line of defense against distraction
• How to develop a high-agency mindset
• Advice for leaders on helping employees improve focus in the workplace

recommandationVideos.Title: Putin tells Tucker Carlson Russia he has no interest in invading Nato countries | BBC News
recommandationVideos.Description:
President Vladimir Putin has insisted that Russia has no interest in invading Poland, Latvia or other Nato countries, calling such a scenario "absolutely out of the question".

The comments came during a lengthy interview that was conducted in the Kremlin with former Fox News host, Tucker Carlson.

The interview was broadcast on the Tucker Carlson Network. Russia's president accused Nato member states of trying to intimidate people with what he called an imaginary Russian threat.

It's the first time the Russian leader has sat down with a Western journalist since Russia invaded Ukraine in 2022.

recommandationVideos.Title: Key takeaways from Tucker Carlson's interview with Russia's Putin | DW News
recommandationVideos.Description:
Russia's President Vladimir Putin has given his first one-on-one interview to Western media since 2019 – to a controversial right-wing US talk show host.

Tucker Carlson is a former Fox News host, a key ally of 2024 election candidate Donald Trump – and a vocal opponent to US military aid for Ukraine. He travelled to Moscow to conduct the interview, which was broadcast on the 'Tucker Carlson Network'. The Russian president used the occasion to push for recognition of Moscow's interests – depicting Russia as a victim of Western betrayal and fearmongering.

Carlson left Putin largely unchallenged. In video from Tucker Carlson Network, some questions led to jokes rather than real answers.

For more on this, we talk to our correspondents William Glucroft and Roman Goncharenko, who are standing by to help us.

recommandationVideos.Title: Por que o cabelo é tão importante no movimento negro
recommandationVideos.Description:
Antes de serem traficados e enviados para as Américas, muitos africanos carregavam na cabeça um símbolo que ia além da estética: o cabelo.

A forma, o corte e os adereços podiam representar origens, etnias, religiões, status social.

Mas já no caminho para as colônias americanas, entre elas o Brasil, essa relação era rompida.

Neste vídeo, nosso repórter Vitor Tavares viaja no tempo para explicar por que o cabelo é tão importante para o movimento negro até os dias de hoje.

Assista e confira.

Reportagem em texto:
https://www.bbc.com/portuguese/brasil-56670268

recommandationVideos.Title: Frantz Fanon: Pele negra, máscaras brancas.
recommandationVideos.Description: Frantz Fanon publicou seu livro 'Pele negra, máscaras brancas em 1952. Médico, culto, sensível e ativista, exerceu com este  e outros trabalhos, uma relevante influência sobre pensadores do 'Terceiro Mundo'. Desnudou, de modo incansável, a relação entre negros e brancos, relação marcada pelo racismo e seu horror. No Brasil, os 'diversos racismos' permanecem, em geral, não ditos, manifestando-se de modos e níveis diversos, carecendo de reconhecimento e enfrentamento. O estudo da obra de Fanon se impõe, mais do que nunca, entre nós.

recommandationVideos.Title: Tohmajärveltä taistellen Syvärille 1941
recommandationVideos.Description:
Jalkaväkirykmentti 9. perustettiin kesäkuussa 1941 Kontiolahdessa 9. prikaatin varusmiehistä ja Pohjois-Karjalan suojeluskuntapiirin reservijoukoista. Rykmentti liitettiin eversti Antero Svenssonin 7. divisioonaan yhdessä jalkaväkirykmenttien 30 ja 51 kanssa. 
Karjalan Armeijan joukko-osastot etenivät valtakunnanrajan yli vanhaan Suomen karjalaan 10. heinäkuuta kello 17.00 alkaen. Eteneminen vanhan Suomen Karjalan alueella jatkui rankkojen taistelujen saattelemana aina Sortavalaan saakka, jonne saavuttiin 15. elokuuta 1941.
Etenemistä jatkettiin 23. elokuuta Koivuselkään ja siletä edelleen Uomaan kylään. Elokuun lopussa 1941 rykmentti ylitti vanhan rajan Käsnäselän ja Kolatselän välissä. Jalkaväkirykmentti yhdeksän taisteli syyskuussa Aunukseen kuuluvissa Nirkan, Pyhäjärven, Kaskanan ja Latvan erämaissa lokakuun alkuun saakka. 
Syvärin joki ylitettiin 6. lokakuuta 1941 kolmannella yrityskerralla. Marraskuussa 1941 eteneminen päättyi Ostan, Goran ja Horomovitsin linjalle. Näissä asemissa Jalkaväkirykmentti yhdeksän oli kesään 1944 saakka.
Tällä videolla kerron kesän ja syksyn 1941 JR 9:n taisteluista Tohmajärveltä aina Syvärin taakse Levinaan ja Baranyn takaisiin kyliin saakka.  Lähteenä tällä videolla olen käyttänyt sotapäiväkirjoja ja kolmea 2010-luvulla tekemiäni sotakirjoja. Kirjojen tekemisen taustalla oli isäni ja hänen neljä veljeä, jotka palvelivat koko sodan ajan Jalkaväkirykementti yhdeksän eri pataljoonissa.
Isäni toimi jatkosodan aikana II/JR 9 konekiväärimiehenä. Hänen esimiehenä oli lähes koko sodan ajan Mannerheim-ristin ritari Ahti Vuorensola.

recommandationVideos.Title: #China, #pakistan #ladakh Front: Roads Are Like Trees. Plant One & A Forest Develops: DG, BRO
recommandationVideos.Description:
Chiling, Ladakh: "Making a road is a measure of a nation's sovereignty. It exercises command and control, and it says that these are my people". Lt Gen Raghu Srinivasan, the Director General of the Border Roads Organisation (BRO) says of the critical road connectivity being built up in Eastern Ladakh and Siachen in the backdrop of the two-front threat from China and Pakistan. In this exclusive interview with StratNews Global's Amitabh P. Revi on the frozen Zanskar River 'Chadar' Trail at Chiling near Leh in Ladakh, the DG notes "The impetus has over the last five or six years been a surge in what we are planning to do and are doing in Ladakh. The amount of projects which are being planned at the National and the Union Territory levels, the amount of funding, which is provided, and the way that projects are being cleared, all of it is phenomenal. We've not seen anything like it." Watch the complete interview with Lt Gen Raghu Srinivasan, the DG of the BRO in our series, 'The Himalayan Frontier'. Part V.

On the differences in road infrastructure in China-occupied Tibet and across the LAC, Lt Gen Srinivasan points out, "the Tibetan Plateau is at a lower altitude-between 12000 to 14000 feet. And it's a flat tabletop. There are no mountain ranges. So, whatever you're constructing is on a flat piece of ground. That's number one. Number two, the mountains are the watershed. That means whatever snow or moisture is going to come is going to stop in our portion. Tibet really is a flat, barren, cold desert. For anyone who constructs roads, moisture or water is a great enemy. That's what we need to work on. And see that we have ways by which we have adequate drainage. So whatever roads we construct are not washed away. Then starting from the south, you have the great Himalayan range, the Ladakh Range, and the Karakoram. There are a series of ranges. We have a very fragile mountain base. They are young mountains in terms of the Himalayas, and these are landslide-prone. With moisture, they become avalanche-prone and naturally you keep ascending, and you keep gaining height and then keep descending and losing height. So, the zig-zags that we have in each of these is essentially to get over a series of mountain ranges, which we have over an expanse of Ladakh, which is approximately 60,000 square kilometres".

SNG's team of Amitabh P. Revi, Rohit Pandita, and Karan Marwaha documented their journey to Leh on the strategic third, alternate axis—the Darcha-Padam-Nimu (NPD) Road, in episode III and episode IV. The route provides critical connectivity for defence logistics to and civilian
development around the Northern China-occupied Tibet border or Line of Actual Control (LAC), the Line of Control (LoC), and the Actual Ground Position Line (AGPL) in Siachen with Pakistan. It is shielded from both the India-China border and the frontier with Pakistan, unlike the other two axes. StratNews Global's team travels during the fourth winter of India's forward deployment post Xi Jinping's aggression that led to the deadly Galwan clashes in 2020. The freezing temperatures highlight one of the several challenges the BRO faces in recce-ing, tracing, drilling through the mighty ranges, and building black-top roads on this route. India's infrastructure development has seen a sustained thrust, especially after China's People's Liberation Army (PLA) salami-slicing tactics in border areas.

recommandationVideos.Title: ‘Absolutely absurd’: Rowan Atkinson blamed for EV plunge
recommandationVideos.Description:
Actor and Comedian Rowan Atkinson has been blamed for the slump in electric car sales, according to the House of Lords. 

Stepmates Studios’ Mark Nicholson says this is “absolutely absurd”.
 
“Rowan Atkinson; he’s actually a really clever guy, he’s got a degree in engineering – he knows his stuff,” he told Sky News host Chris Kenny. 

“He got duped by the electric car industry – that's all he did; he just said, ‘hey, I got duped, maybe you will too, just be cautious’. 

“I think he should lean into; I think we should see Mr Bean goes electric as a new film or something.”

recommandationVideos.Title: Putin tells Tucker Carlson Russia he has no interest in invading Nato countries | BBC News
recommandationVideos.Description:
President Vladimir Putin has insisted that Russia has no interest in invading Poland, Latvia or other Nato countries, calling such a scenario "absolutely out of the question".

The comments came during a lengthy interview that was conducted in the Kremlin with former Fox News host, Tucker Carlson.

The interview was broadcast on the Tucker Carlson Network. Russia's president accused Nato member states of trying to intimidate people with what he called an imaginary Russian threat.

It's the first time the Russian leader has sat down with a Western journalist since Russia invaded Ukraine in 2022.

recommandationVideos.Title: Mr Bean actor Rowan Atkinson blamed for decline of EV sales in United Kingdom
recommandationVideos.Description:
Sky News host James Macpherson says Mr Bean actor Rowan Atkinson has been named and blamed for the slowdown in EV sales in the United Kingdom.

“The sale of EVs in the UK has slowed down so much the government has halved its sales forecasts,” Mr Macpherson said.

“The government had planned that by 2027 67 per cent of all new cars sold would be EVs.

“Now they’re saying it is only going to be about 38 per cent.”

Mr Bean actor Rowan Atkinson is the culprit according to the House of Lords for the decline in EV popularity.
recommandationVideos.Author: Sky News Australia

recommandationVideos.Title: Key takeaways from Tucker Carlson's interview with Russia's Putin | DW News
recommandationVideos.Description:
Russia's President Vladimir Putin has given his first one-on-one interview to Western media since 2019 – to a controversial right-wing US talk show host.

Tucker Carlson is a former Fox News host, a key ally of 2024 election candidate Donald Trump – and a vocal opponent to US military aid for Ukraine. He travelled to Moscow to conduct the interview, which was broadcast on the 'Tucker Carlson Network'. The Russian president used the occasion to push for recognition of Moscow's interests – depicting Russia as a victim of Western betrayal and fearmongering.

Carlson left Putin largely unchallenged. In video from Tucker Carlson Network, some questions led to jokes rather than real answers.

For more on this, we talk to our correspondents William Glucroft and Roman Goncharenko, who are standing by to help us.

recommandationVideos.Title: Kharkiv: Seven killed after Russia drone hits petrol station in Ukraine I BBC News
recommandationVideos.Description:
At least seven people have been killed in an overnight Russian drone attack that hit a petrol station in Kharkiv, officials said.

The drones caused large fires in a residential area in the east of the city, regional head Oleh Syniehubov said.

Five members of one family, including a baby and two children, were among the victims, he said.

Russia's military has made no public comments on the reported strikes.

recommandationVideos.Title: America Was Wrong About Ethanol - Study Shows
recommandationVideos.Description:
Using Corn For Fuel Seems Like A Dumb Idea In Light Of New Research
Subscribe to Engineering Explained for more videos! - https://goo.gl/VZstk7
Recommended Books & Car Products - http://amzn.to/2BrekJm
EE Shirts! - http://bit.ly/2BHsiuo

Ethanol makes up 10% of most of the gasoline sold in the United States. A large part of why Ethanol is so prevalent is that the Renewable Fuel Standard, created in 2005, wanted to reduce the emissions of the fuels we use. Ethanol created from corn is renewable, because the corn takes carbon from the atmosphere to grow, creating a cycle that minimizes how much carbon is added to the atmosphere. At least, that's the story we were told.

New research out of University of Wisconsin - Madison, suggests that "the carbon intensity of corn ethanol is no less than gasoline and likely at least 24% higher." What's the solution? We need to choose options that have a greater percentage of net emissions reductions, so that we don't unintentionally increase emissions if regulators estimated predictions are incorrect.

recommandationVideos.Title: Has ADANI made a COMEBACK? | Abhi and Niyu
recommandationVideos.Description:
In this video, let's understand Adani's secret to success after the Hindenburg report. Adani recently reclaimed the spot of being the richest Indian despite the Hindenburg crisis and numerous allegations. In this case study there are many lessons for entrepreneurs, and young Indians about how to tackle a crisis and come out stronger.

#Adani #modi #abhiandniyu 

A video by Abhiraj Rajadhyaksha & Niyati Mavinkurve

Who is Gautam Adani?

Gautam Adani is a self-made Indian billionaire and the chairman of the Adani Group, a globally integrated infrastructure player with interests in commodities, logistics, energy, and others. Born in 1962 in Ahmedabad, Gujarat, Adani embarked on his entrepreneurial journey at a young age, initially working in the diamond brokerage business before establishing the Adani Group in 1988. His vision and acumen have steered the conglomerate into becoming one of India's largest and most influential companies. Known for his resilience and strategic foresight, Adani's story is a testament to the power of ambition and persistence in achieving global business success.

How Adani is connected to PM Modi?
Gautam Adani's connection to Prime Minister Narendra Modi often comes under scrutiny and discussion, primarily because both hail from Gujarat, India. Their association is frequently highlighted in the context of Adani Group's significant growth over the past few years, coinciding with Modi's tenure in office, first as the Chief Minister of Gujarat and then as the Prime Minister of India. Critics argue that Adani's enterprises have benefited from what they perceive as close ties to Modi's government, pointing to the rapid expansion of infrastructure projects, energy initiatives, and defense contracts awarded to his companies.

Supporters of Modi and Adani counter these claims by emphasizing the Adani Group's capabilities, efficiency, and the competitive nature of the bidding processes for government contracts. They argue that the group's success is not a result of political favoritism but rather strategic decision-making, innovation, and an ability to execute large-scale projects effectively.

It's important to navigate these discussions with a balanced perspective, recognizing the complex interplay between politics and business in India. The relationship between Modi and Adani illustrates broader themes of corporate governance, public policy, and economic development in a rapidly growing economy.

recommandationVideos.Title: Putin tells Tucker Carlson Russia he has no interest in invading Nato countries | BBC News
recommandationVideos.Description:
President Vladimir Putin has insisted that Russia has no interest in invading Poland, Latvia or other Nato countries, calling such a scenario "absolutely out of the question".

The comments came during a lengthy interview that was conducted in the Kremlin with former Fox News host, Tucker Carlson.

The interview was broadcast on the Tucker Carlson Network. Russia's president accused Nato member states of trying to intimidate people with what he called an imaginary Russian threat.

It's the first time the Russian leader has sat down with a Western journalist since Russia invaded Ukraine in 2022.

recommandationVideos.Title: Woman who lost limbs in Tube accident seeks Sadiq Khan meeting
Keywords: Woman who lost limbs in Tube accident
legal battle against Transport for London
recommandationVideos.Description:
A public relations executive who lost her right arm and leg after being hit by two Tube trains has called on Sadiq Khan, the London mayor, to meet her to discuss Transport for London’s “outdated” attitude to safety.

Sarah de Lagarde, 46, slipped on a wet and uneven platform at High Barnet station in north London in September 2022 and fell down the gap between the train and the platform. No one heard her cries for help after she broke her nose and two teeth in the fall. After being hit by two trains she was rushed to hospital, where her limbs were amputated.

De Lagarde, who now uses two prosthetic limbs, has launched a legal battle against Transport for London (TfL), which, she says, has not accepted responsibility for what happened.

recommandationVideos.Title: Key takeaways from Tucker Carlson's interview with Russia's Putin | DW News
recommandationVideos.Description:
Russia's President Vladimir Putin has given his first one-on-one interview to Western media since 2019 – to a controversial right-wing US talk show host.

Tucker Carlson is a former Fox News host, a key ally of 2024 election candidate Donald Trump – and a vocal opponent to US military aid for Ukraine. He travelled to Moscow to conduct the interview, which was broadcast on the 'Tucker Carlson Network'. The Russian president used the occasion to push for recognition of Moscow's interests – depicting Russia as a victim of Western betrayal and fearmongering.

Carlson left Putin largely unchallenged. In video from Tucker Carlson Network, some questions led to jokes rather than real answers.

For more on this, we talk to our correspondents William Glucroft and Roman Goncharenko, who are standing by to help us.

recommandationVideos.Title: “Why Are You Shouting Like A Commando?”, Vice-President Jagdeep Dhankhar Gets Furious In Rajya Sabha
recommandationVideos.Description:
Rajya Sabha Chairman and Vice-President Jagdeep Dhankhar strongly criticized the Opposition on Saturday for disrupting parliamentary discussions on the Bharat Ratna award for former Prime Minister Chaudhary Charan Singh. Dhankhar, visibly frustrated, attempted to restore order in the house and urged Opposition members, including Congress leader Jairam Ramesh, to calm down, questioning Ramesh with, "Why are you shouting like a commando?"

Earlier, during the proceedings, the Opposition objected when RLD chief Jayant Chaudhary was permitted to speak about his grandfather receiving the Bharat Ratna Award from VP Dhankar.

In response to the objections, Dhankar called out Rajya Sabha Leader of Opposition Mallikarjun Kharge, stating, "Either control your people or rise and address the house."

recommandationVideos.Title: #China, #pakistan #ladakh Front: Roads Are Like Trees. Plant One & A Forest Develops: DG, BRO
recommandationVideos.Description:
Chiling, Ladakh: "Making a road is a measure of a nation's sovereignty. It exercises command and control, and it says that these are my people". Lt Gen Raghu Srinivasan, the Director General of the Border Roads Organisation (BRO) says of the critical road connectivity being built up in Eastern Ladakh and Siachen in the backdrop of the two-front threat from China and Pakistan. In this exclusive interview with StratNews Global's Amitabh P. Revi on the frozen Zanskar River 'Chadar' Trail at Chiling near Leh in Ladakh, the DG notes "The impetus has over the last five or six years been a surge in what we are planning to do and are doing in Ladakh. The amount of projects which are being planned at the National and the Union Territory levels, the amount of funding, which is provided, and the way that projects are being cleared, all of it is phenomenal. We've not seen anything like it." Watch the complete interview with Lt Gen Raghu Srinivasan, the DG of the BRO in our series, 'The Himalayan Frontier'. Part V.

On the differences in road infrastructure in China-occupied Tibet and across the LAC, Lt Gen Srinivasan points out, "the Tibetan Plateau is at a lower altitude-between 12000 to 14000 feet. And it's a flat tabletop. There are no mountain ranges. So, whatever you're constructing is on a flat piece of ground. That's number one. Number two, the mountains are the watershed. That means whatever snow or moisture is going to come is going to stop in our portion. Tibet really is a flat, barren, cold desert. For anyone who constructs roads, moisture or water is a great enemy. That's what we need to work on. And see that we have ways by which we have adequate drainage. So whatever roads we construct are not washed away. Then starting from the south, you have the great Himalayan range, the Ladakh Range, and the Karakoram. There are a series of ranges. We have a very fragile mountain base. They are young mountains in terms of the Himalayas, and these are landslide-prone. With moisture, they become avalanche-prone and naturally you keep ascending, and you keep gaining height and then keep descending and losing height. So, the zig-zags that we have in each of these is essentially to get over a series of mountain ranges, which we have over an expanse of Ladakh, which is approximately 60,000 square kilometres".

SNG's team of Amitabh P. Revi, Rohit Pandita, and Karan Marwaha documented their journey to Leh on the strategic third, alternate axis—the Darcha-Padam-Nimu (NPD) Road, in episode III and episode IV. The route provides critical connectivity for defence logistics to and civilian
development around the Northern China-occupied Tibet border or Line of Actual Control (LAC), the Line of Control (LoC), and the Actual Ground Position Line (AGPL) in Siachen with Pakistan. It is shielded from both the India-China border and the frontier with Pakistan, unlike the other two axes. StratNews Global's team travels during the fourth winter of India's forward deployment post Xi Jinping's aggression that led to the deadly Galwan clashes in 2020. The freezing temperatures highlight one of the several challenges the BRO faces in recce-ing, tracing, drilling through the mighty ranges, and building black-top roads on this route. India's infrastructure development has seen a sustained thrust, especially after China's People's Liberation Army (PLA) salami-slicing tactics in border areas.

recommandationVideos.Title: Ian Bremmer on Putin and Tucker | Quick Take
recommandationVideos.Description:
What happened when Tucker Carlson met Vladimir Putin? Was it news, propaganda, theatre, or all three? Ian Bremmer breaks down what you need to know now in his latest Quick Take. 

Subscribe to GZERO on YouTube and turn on notifications (🔔): http://www.youtube.com/@GZEROMedia 
Sign up for GZERO Daily (free newsletter on global politics): https://rebrand.ly/gzeronewsletter

Ian Bremmer weighs in on Tucker Carlson's highly-anticipated interview with Putin and why it revealed what he and all other megalomaniacs have in common. The two-hour sit-down dropped to much fanfare from all sides of the political spectrum. Will there be any fallout from Putin’s first interview with an American since the start of the “special military operation” in Ukraine? Ian breaks down what you need to know in his latest Quick Take.

Hi, everybody. Ian Bremmer here. And a Quick Take, but towards the end of your week. Why? Because a lot of us watched this interview between Vladimir Putin and Tucker Carlson. And isn't there a lot to talk about? And the answer is a little less than all of the hype but still worth discussing.

First, I mean, you know, I will admit to having posted a fair bit about the importance of this interview. Of course, in part, it's because I have a history talking about, studying, covering Russia. But also, because this is now entering almost the third year of war when the Russians have invaded Ukraine, it is increasingly not going very well for the Ukrainians and therefore not very well for the United States and its allies. And that means that the timing of this interview is important, especially in the context of a very heated, very divisive US election, when increasingly support for Ukraine is becoming a matter of political difference. And it wasn't six months ago, but it certainly is becoming so very rapidly now.

Secondly, I have absolutely no problem with the idea of interviewing dictators. I think it's important for people to understand what makes everyone tick - friends, adversaries, everyone around the world. The problem is, of course, that dictators usually don't respect free press. And in Russia in particular, the media is, an independent media shut down, and they're imprisoned. They're sometimes assassinated. And certainly, Putin is not someone that has a history of valuing people that ask him independent minded, tough questions.

recommandationVideos.Description:

“If Canadians are going to believe this leader of the opposition, he needs to come clean with who is funding his organization,” he said.

Poilievre also repeated his accusation that carbon pricing has contributed to food inflation – a claim which Trudeau said there is no evidence to support.

recommandationVideos.Title: On Bullsh*t Jobs | David Graeber | RSA Replay
recommandationVideos.Description:
In 2013 David Graeber, professor of anthropology at LSE, wrote an excoriating essay on modern work for Strike! magazine. “On the Phenomenon of Bullshit Jobs” was read over a million times and the essay translated in seventeen different languages within weeks. Graeber visits the RSA to expand on this phenomenon, and will explore how the proliferation of meaningless jobs - more associated with the 20th-century Soviet Union than latter-day capitalism - has impacted modern society. In doing so, he looks at how we value work, and how, rather than being productive, work has become an end in itself; the way such work maintains the current broken system of finance capital; and, finally, how we can get out of it.

recommandationVideos.Title: Political blooper: MP's Scottish accent baffles British parliamentarian
recommandationVideos.Description:
Members of the British parliament broke into laughter on October 18 when New-Zealand born Tory MP, Paul Beresford, visibly struggled to understand his Scottish colleague who was speaking with an accent.

Beresford initially apologized to Scottish National Party's (SNP) David Linden before asking him to repeat his question. But after a second attempt he sheepishly suggested Linden speak more slowly.

After two failed attempts in the miscommunication, Deputy Speaker, Lindsay Hoyle, suggested they resolve the matter by letter.

recommandationVideos.Description:
Labour MP Dennis Skinner has been suspended from Parliament for the day for calling the Prime Minister "dodgy Dave". recommandationVideos.Title: UK PM 'regrets' Jallianwala Bagh massacre: 'Shameful scar in our history'
recommandationVideos.Description: Days before the hundredth anniversary of the Jallianwala Bagh massacre, the British Prime Minister expressed regret over the incident. Theresa May called it a shameful scar in British-Indian history. Following the expression of regret, PM May hoped that UK's ties with India grow stronger. On April 13, 1919, British General Dyer shut the gates of the Jallianwala Bagh in Amritsar and opened indiscriminate fire on civilians. The firing continued for about 10 minutes, and an estimated 1,000 people were killed while another 1,500 were injured.

recommandationVideos.Title: British MP Tanmanjeet Singh Dhesi slams Boris Johnson over racist remarks
recommandationVideos.Description: British MP Tanmanjeet Singh Dhesi launched a scathing attack on PM Boris Johnson over his past remarks on Muslim women. He demanded an apology from Johnson and said that such remarks have led to a surge in hate crimes in the country. Mr Dhesi received applause from fellow Opposition Labour party MPs. Dhesi, who is the first turban-wearing Sikh MP in British history also challenged the British prime minister to order an investigation into alleged Islamophobia within his own Conservative Party.

recommandationVideos.Title: British Sikh MP demands apology from UK PM Boris Johnson over ‘racist remarks'
recommandationVideos.Description:
Britain's first turbaned Sikh MP, Tanmanjeet Singh Dhesi, on Wednesday demanded that British Prime Minister Boris Johnson apologise for “racist” remarks against Muslim women in the past. "For those of us who, from a young age, have had to endure and face up to being called names such as towelhead or Taliban, or to people saying we come from bongo, bongo land, we can appreciate full well the hurt and pain felt by already vulnerable Muslim women when they are described as looking like bank robbers and letterboxes," said Dhesi, in reference to Johnson's column in ‘The Daily Telegraph' newspaper last year.
